  "response": "The Nikon 55-200mm lens can be used for portraits, but it has some pros and cons:\n\nPros:\n1. Good focal length range (55-200mm)\n2. Allows comfortable distance from subject\n3. Provides nice background compression\n4. Creates pleasing background blur (bokeh)\n5. Relatively affordable\n\nCons:\n1. Variable/slower aperture (typically f/4-5.6)\n2. Less ideal in low light conditions\n3. Not as sharp as prime portrait lenses\n4. Limited depth of field compared to wider aperture lenses\n\nFor best portrait results:\n- Use focal lengths between 85-135mm\n- Choose longer focal lengths (85mm-105mm)\n- Prefer lens with wider maximum aperture (f/1.8 or f/2.8)\n\nRecommendations for better portrait lenses:\n1. Nikon 85mm f/1.8G\n2. Nikon 50mm f/1.8G\n3. Sigma 85mm f/1.4 Art\n\nWhile the 55-200mm can work for portraits, specialized portrait lenses will typically produce superior results.",
